subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Male. Head broadly rounded with swollen kidney or C-shaped compound eyes laterally, folded posteriorly (
Figs 1, 3
). Vertex a little elevated, with doubled protuberances terminally, separated by a cleft (
Fig. 1
). Posterolateral margins of eyes with 6–7 alveoli of supraocular bristles on both sides. Eyes separated, eye bridge divided by sixteen facet diameters (
Figs 1, 2
) and formed by 4–5 facet rows (
Fig. 2
). Ratio of distance of apices of eyes (tangential points) to minimum width of frons approximately 1.2:1. Dorsal 1/3 of the eye section three times as narrow as ventral 2/3. Frontal suture vestigial, limited to prolonged horizontal rods on both sides and two sclerotized patches in the middle (
Fig. 2
). Head setose in anterior as well as posterior parts (
Figs 1, 3
). Scar patch above the upper apices of eyes is divided, slightly convex near vertical axis. The frontoclypeus has two vertical quite separated alveoli patches expanded laterally to the basis of antennae. Antennae (
Figs 4, 5
) of 16 articles. Scape almost cylindrical, twice as long as pedicel which is globular; scales lancet-shaped, a little longer than pedicel diameter. Basal flagellomeres spindle-shaped, medial ones approximately pitcher-shaped with nodes bulbose, slightly asymmetrical and reduced internodes (necks). Antennomeres 13–15 fused, swollen basally, terminal antennomere globular. Last four antennomeres very dark in contrast to the preceding ones. Ascoids paired, palmate, with five branches. Mouthparts extending slightly beyond basal palp segment. For the labellum, as shown in 
Fig. 1
, the convergent lines of spines between both lobes are visible. Labellum bulbose, without digital protuberances in between (
Fig. 10
). Length ratio of maxillary palps 1.0:2.1:2.1: 2.7, segment 4 not annulate (
Fig. 9
). Ratio of maximum length of cibarium to length of epipharynx 2.3:1 (
Figs 1
, 
11
), labrum setose.

Male genitalia with ejaculatory apodeme cane-shaped, sheltered between gonocoxites, not expanded laterally at basis, proximally circular (bag-shaped), with paired petal-shaped sclerites inside (
Figs 15, 18
). Aedeagal complex conical and approximately pintle or thumb-shaped, hooked terminally (
Figs 15, 16, 18
), with a spineshaped lateral element protruding in the middle, shorter than gonostyle. Gonocoxites elongate (
Figs 15, 17, 18
), almost cylindrical, basally with gonocoxal apodemes, touched in midline, inner pair only tongue-shaped, separated in vertical axis of genitalia. Ratio of maximum length of gonocoxite (including basal lobuli) and aedeagal complex 1:1.1. Gonocoxites 1.9 times as long as pear-shaped gonostyli with four bristles terminally, of which two are minute. Epandrium oblong-shaped, bare (
Figs 14
, 
18
), central aperture prolonged, savoy biscuit-shaped, ventral plate not observed. Hypandrium stripe-shaped (
Figs 15, 18
). Hypoproct collar-shaped, with two deep narrow clefts distally on both sides and central tongue-shaped projection, annulated in the middle and haired terminally (
Figs 8
, 
14
, 
18
). Epiproct fold-shaped, haired. Epandrial clasping lobes with enlarged bases and slender, strongly arched blade, slightly enlarged in distal half, three times as long as epandrium, with three brush-like tenacula (
Figs 14
, 
18
).
